	that the number of galaxies in a halo scale approximately as the mass to
	the 0.8th power in the high-mass limit. These constraints are
	independent of those derived from the luminosity function or
	Tully-Fisher relation. We also predict the power spectrum, bispectrum,
	and higher order moments of the mass density field in this framework.
	Although halo models agree well with measurements of the mass power
	spectrum and the higher order Sp parameters in N-body
	simulations, the model assumption that halos are spherical leads to
	disagreement in the configuration dependence of the bispectrum at small
	scales. We stress the importance of finite-volume effects in higher
	order statistics and show how they can be estimated in this approach.},
